## Lore — project knowledge graph

This project uses [Lore](https://github.com/…/lore) to persist the **business
knowledge** of the codebase as a typed graph: modules, capabilities, flows,
events, rules, forms, entities and decisions. The graph lives in
`.lore/lore.db` and is reached through the MCP tools whose names start with
`lore_`.

Treat Lore as **living documentation**. When you work on this project:

### Always read before acting

Before answering a question about how the system works, or before writing
non-trivial code, **consult the graph first**. Prefer:

- `lore_query(text_or_id, depth)` — flexible search by id, title substring
  or tag. A good first call for most questions.
- `lore_find_variants(capability_id)` — "how many ways of doing X?"
- `lore_traverse(from_id, relations, max_depth)` — impact analysis
  ("what breaks if I touch X?").
- `lore_get_node(id)` — full detail + incoming/outgoing edges.

If the user's question maps to a node you know exists, cite the node id.

### Detect contradictions

If a user instruction or a piece of code contradicts what the graph says
(e.g. "the refund flow goes through stripe" but `refund-flow.metadata.provider`
is `"adyen"`), **surface the contradiction** before acting. Ask which one is
correct. Do not silently pick one.

### Update the graph as work happens

When you or the user make a decision that matters to the system's behavior,
**record it**:

- A new flow or capability appears → `lore_add_node` + appropriate edges.
- An existing flow changes substantially → `lore_update_node` with the new
  title/body; optionally mark the old one `status="deprecated"` and link via
  `supersedes`.
- A new dependency, trigger or validation → `lore_add_edge`.
- A design decision → `decision` node + `references` edge from the flow/rule
  that motivated it.

Favor **few, well-named nodes** over many tiny ones. Use kebab-case ids
(`payment-by-transfer`, not `payment_by_transfer`). Group outgoing edges by
relation. Keep bodies short (≤ 10 lines); the graph is a map, not the terrain.

### Keep the graph healthy

- Before large structural edits, run `lore_audit()` and clean the warnings.
- If a node becomes unreachable, either delete it or link it.
- Export to markdown (`lore_export_markdown(".lore/export")`) for code review
  when changes are significant.

### Slash commands available

- `/lore-init` — bootstrap the graph in a new project.
- `/lore-recent` — show what was updated recently.
- `/lore-audit` — run health checks.
- `/lore-show <id>` — full detail of a node.
- `/lore-impact <id>` — what touches this node.

